    <item>
      <title>An Awakening</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Roleplaying&amp;message.id=12460#M12460</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT size=2&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I didn't really understand what was happening to me. I was feverish and flushed and it felt as though a smiths hammer were beating against the inside of my head. An odd rash appeared and began to spread. Welts rose on my head and face. And dreams. Strange dreams of places unknown to me. They told me that in my sleep I uttered words in a strange language. At times I felt myself delirious. Voices called to me to "come home", voices that only I could hear. In my sleep I beheld visions of strange places and creatures...and dragons. The visions should have frightened me but they did not, in fact I found them to be somehow comforting. I spoke of these things to my mother but she would only shush me and tell me that they would pass when the fever abated and to mention them no more. My mother loved me as she did all her children. It was dangerous for her to show it, but she managed to let me know in spite of my father's ire. A whipered word of praise, a brief smile or fleeting hug. Sometimes just a wisp of a look, but it was enough. In time it seemed that we could communicate without words, indeed she could almost read my mind. There was no secret I could keep from her but that she would read it in my face.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;My father was afraid that I has the plague and sent me out to sleep in the old empty barn. My sisters and brothers were afraid of me and kept away, only occaisionally peering in through the crack of the open door...when it was left open. My mother said nothing at all, but simply tended to me with a worried look and assured me that everything would be alright. And that last was what disturbed me the most. Because I knew she was lying.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The isolation did not bother me. Often I had wished for it. I had always been different. All of my family had fair skin and hair. They had eyes the color of the summer sky but I was dark. I think that my father considered me to be someones illegitimate son. He certainly did not show me the favor that is the custom with the eldest son. Instead he treated me more like a servant, and a poor one at that. Beatings were frequent and when he was in his cups I would find ways to avoid him, for those times were the worst. I learned to hide in corners and nooks and other dark places until I could do it nearly at will. I kept a small knife with me and practiced with it when I could find time to myself. Beatings I could endure, but when he was drunk I feared for my life. Those times he did not know when to stop. When he was sober the beatings would come, but those I could survive. He needed me to be able to work in the forge and so was able to restrain himself...to a point.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;My chores were always the hardest, the dirtiest and the longest. He said it was because I was the oldest but when the others had reached an age to be of some help he always found other things for them to do. I was always the last. The last to eat, the last for a winter coat, the last for everything. My brothers and sisters seemed indifferent to me. There was no rivalry between us as they came before me in all things. They did not hate me but the fact that I was different from them was all too obvious and they were not afraid to point this out, often and sometimes at great length. I bear them no ill will, such are the ways of children.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Illegitimate.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I wished&amp;nbsp;for this to be true. Perhaps one day my real father might come and rescue me from my prison, for that is how I saw my condition. But by the time I began to grow into a man I knew this would not happen. This was not a childrens story to be told at bedtime. There would be no fairy princess or noble prince to carry me away. No "happily ever after". This was to be my lot in life, that of a smithy's son, and an unwanted one at that. The only hope for me was that I learned the craft well and when I was old enough I would leave for Freeport or Qeynos and make my living there instead of Highpass where everyone knew me.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I had planned to leave on my eighteenth birthday. All was prepared. I had managed to beg an extra shirt and pants from my mother. I did not have to tell her why nor did she ask, but I have no doubt that she knew. I was able to secure an handful of coppers by running errands for certain discreet merchants and tradesmen in Highpass. It was not much but I could afford enough food to take me where I chose to go.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Then came the illness and all my plans were laid for nought. While I lay sensless in fever my father found my outfit. He took the coppers for himself and the clothes he gave away. He came to my bed in a rage but the fear of the plague was upon him and he would not touch me. I think I would have died that night had I been sound.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I still do not know how long I lay in bed. A week at least I think, perhaps longer. I only know that one morning I awoke and found the fever had abated. I was ravenously hungry and decided to dress and go into the house to find something to eat. I should have been worried about my father but I was not. Perhaps I was lucky or perhaps he was, but fate had him away from the forge on an errand when I rose and began to dress. As I pulled my old tunic over my head it snagged and tore slightly. I finished pulling it on and then put my hand to my head to see why the shirt had snagged and felt...horns a row of them. On my forehead and beneath my eyes. Small, but pointed and sharp. I reached for my breeches and when I looked down I saw that where the rash had been there was now a long, dark design, like a tatoo. It ran the full lenth of my body from my feet to my head. I assumed it went down my back as well. and it was...beautiful! Suddenly all that had gone before thjis morning no longer mattered and I laughed out loud. All of the toil and anguish, the beatings, the insults and the bitterness was gone from my mind in an instant. At that same moment a word came into my mind. A word I knew but had not thought about, it being such a rare thing. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Drakkin. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I was a Drakkin, one of the guardians of Veeshan The blood of these creatures flowed through &lt;I&gt;my&lt;/I&gt; veins. Suddenly the dreams made sense. It was part of my awakening. I was being shown who I really was and where I needed to go. A place where I would at last find welcome. A place that I could truly call home. At that thought a powerful longing arose in me and I knew that I must leave at once for Crescent Reach, the city of the Dragon Kin and home to all manner of adventurous folk. I almost forgot my hunger...almost... and thought to leave straight away. But the ravening within me was too powerful to ignore.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I finished dressing and stepped out ofthe barn. It was a fine, bright day and my brother was hard at work at the forge. Making horseshoes I think. As he saw me coming he set the tongs on the anvil.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"It's about time!" he said. "Father has much for you to do, we have been sorely..."&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;He stopped talking as he got his first good look at me, his jaw hanging open like a yawning cave.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"Dad is going to be so pissed." he said softly. "No one is going to want to do business with a...Drakkin." I could only laugh.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I put my hand on his shoulder and smiled. "Don't worry, they won't have to." I said.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;My brother nodded and looked resigned. His work load was about to increase...a lot. He sighed. "No, I don't suppose they will." he said and sighed again.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I left my brother to his thoughts and went into the house. My mother was at the fire toasting some biscuits next to a bubbling pot of stew. She did not look up as I entered the room.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"I thought you might want something to eat before you left." she said, her attention still fixed on the the fire and what was cooking there.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"You thought right." I said, trying to keep my voice light. "As always." I failed. She stood then and turned to me. Her eyes were wet and reddened.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"No," she said, "Not always..." Her voice caught in her throat as she looked up, seeing me fully for the first time.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"How long have you known?" I asked.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"I have always known." She replied. "You are not the first of my kin to be called. But I had hoped it would spare us."&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"Am I hideous to you?" I asked, afraid of what the answer might be.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"No." She replied, running the tips of her fingers lightly across the small points of bone on my face. "Not hideous. You are beautiful."&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;She studied me for a moment, my markings, my small horns. I seemed to have grown a little taller, a little thinner.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"You father..." she began, but I raised a hand to quiet her.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"He will not trouble me." I said. I will be gone before..." This time it was my mother who silenced me.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"He knows." She said. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"He knows?"&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"You did not change overnight. Please," she said, "Do not hate him." But I said nothing.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"I beg you, do not hate him. If anyone has a right to.."&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"If anyone has a right to, it is him." A voice interupted from behind me. I turned.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"Hello father." I said. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"She is right," he said, "You are beautiful." Then he seemed to be at a loss for words. We both were. In his hands he carried a backpack. It was very fine, perhaps the best I had ever seen. The thick leather was tanned and oiled. The stitching was sturdy and precise. It was the kind of thing one might find one of the officers of High Keep going into the field with. Inside it were two changes of clothes and a good cloak of kodiak fur as well as enough food and water to last me much farther than I needed to go. Also inside was a long dagger on a belt. It was a good knife. A soldiers knife.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"I thought you might need these for your trip." He said when he handed them to me. I looked into his eyes to thank him. I don't know what I expected to read there, anger perhaps, or resignation. But what I saw was guilt. Guilt, sorrow and a deep, deep shame. Deeper than words could ever express. He looked away.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"If any one has a right to hate me, it is you." He said. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Here was the man I had once thought a monster. A man incapable of love for me. A man who's only thought for me was how much work I could do for him, how well he could use me like any one of his other tools. But he was not a monster, just a man who has awoken to suddenly find that all the things he had thought and brooded over for 18 years were wrong. It was a change, no less profound for him than mine was for me. And for that I pitied him. Indeed I feared for him, for such changes can destroy a man.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"I am so sorry." He said and his voice began to waver. "After all I have said and after all I have done... I would that you could forgive me." His eyes glistened as he struggled to speak. "I have no right to ask it I know. And were I in your place I do not think I could do it, nor would I expect it of you. If you cannot, I understand." &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I said nothing for a moment.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"If I could undo what I have done..." he went on, but I no longer heard him, I had my answer for him now. I placed my hands on his shoulders and pulled him to me.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;"How can I hate you?" I said, my own voice thick with emotion. "You are my &lt;I&gt;father&lt;/I&gt;." I put my arms around him then and for the first time in my memory we embraced. My mother joined us then.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I left the following morning after eating well and sleeping. My strength has not fully returned to me but the compulsion to depart was too strong to ignore. I last saw my parents standing just outside the door of their little house. My father had his arm around my mother's waist and he held her close as they watched me leave. It was a sight I had longed to see for many years.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;My family are the Drakkin now. My memories of that time when I was human grow fainter with each passing day. The humans I see passing through The Reach seem alien to me and often times I finds myself resenting their presence here. But they pass on and are forgotten as quickly as the came. Someday I may return to where I was born to see what has become of my human family. Or not. I do not know what the future may bring. I only know that here, high in the mountains among the others of my kind, have I found my true family and, finally, I am at peace.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Tjirel on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;10-08-2006&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;11:25 AM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Sun, 08 Oct 2006 18:22:09 GMT</pubDate>
