    <item>
      <title>A Loyal Servant's Tale (thus far)</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Roleplaying&amp;message.id=12456#M12456</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;Chapter 1 Passing Over&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;My last day in the service of Lord Gilliad Shadowbane was spent on a bed in the Temple of Marr. I was dieing from a dose of an incurable slow poison that D`Vinn had given me. I wanted to be among my fellow druids of Karana but I knew that they could not have given me as peaceful a passing as the clerics of Marr had. I opened the music box that Lady Alani had made for me and listened to the melody that issued forth. I remember the first time hearing this melody had evoked erotic feelings in me as memories of a former lover filled my mind. This time was different. The music had a soothing effect that gave me peace and eased the pain that the poison had started inflicting on my as my life slowly drained away. Lord Gilliad was at my side and young Gilliadson was with him.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“I will surely miss you both.” I said. “I have loved you like a son, M’lord.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“I know you have, Willa.” Replied M’lord Gilliad. “During your final moments I do not want you as my servant but as my friend. We are equals Willa.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“As you wish Gilliad.” I always enjoyed these times with Gilliad when we were afforded the chance to be considered on an equal basis. During all my years of service to the House of Shadowbane, I never felt more appreciated than when I served Gilliad. He was a wonderful man. As I lay there, on the bed listening to the music box, Gilliad opened his and the tunes from both boxes intertwined. I felt alive even though I was not going to be much longer. Young Gilliadson opened his box and the music from it joined in with the other two boxes. The melody that they formed together was beautiful. I could see Lady Alani’s face and she was smiling upon me. I do not know if Gilliad and his son saw it too. Gilliad and I talked and the music made me feel strong enough to actually laugh. Yes, I was laughing when I saw the last of the two Shadowbanes. Gilliad and Gilliadson each held one of my hands as I slipped into Karana’s bosom. I had never felt so loved in all my life. Not even when I was in the arms of that former lover.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Willanaome.” Came a whisper that sounded like distant thunder. “Willanaome.” It came again a few seconds later. Somehow, I knew it had to be Karana himself. Why I was so honored to hear him call my name, I do not know. I bowed down to the ground.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Yes M’lord.” &lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Arise my child. You have been among my most faithful and I wish to reward you with another chance at life in the world of Norrath as my servant.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“M’lord I am your servant. Whatever you wish I shall do.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“You will be needed in a future time to assist the House of Shadowbane again. But until such time you must prepare yourself. A young follower of mine is departing Norrath to join me here. You will take over her body. It is not good to put all of your knowledge into such a young body so I will give you a choice. You can either have all the memories of your magic or you may retain your other memories, including those of the Shadowbanes.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“I can relearn the magic, M’lord, but the memories of my life are irreplaceable. You know my heart.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“So shall it be then. You will not reveal yourself to any of the Shadowbanes until you hear from me otherwise. You may however, gather what news of them that you can since you will be aiding them again when the House of Shadowbane is restored.”&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Chapter 2 Return&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Thank you M’lord.” I bowed once more and when I arose, I found myself in the Misty Thicket. I looked at my hands and they were youthful again though they were not my own. I looked around and saw a group of goblins leaving the area where I was now sitting. I looked around me and saw the bodies of several other Halflings, two adults and a child. I bowed my head and wept for them. I was still weeping when the deputies found me and took me to Rivervale. No one knew the names of the dead Halfling family. Somehow, I knew and told them. I also knew the name of the body I had inhabited but I did not use it, instead, I gave them my own.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;It is quite an experience being an old, shriveled up but powerful druid one day and being a young but much weaker one the next. I had no recollection of the magic I had learned in all my years of service to Karana. I did remember my friends, the Shadowbanes. I knew I had to get stronger so I could go out into the world to seek news of them. I also knew that I had to be ready for whatever service I was to give to them when I was finally restored to them. My love for the Shadowbane family had nothing to do with the wages that they paid me. Believe me they paid me quite well. It was more the fact that I had become a family friend to them and was loved, truly loved for the first time in my life. It was not an erotic love that we shared. Oh no, it was a pure kind. The kind that told me that if Gilliad had been there that day he would have given his life up if he knew that I would have been spared. It was an honor to fight alongside Lady Alani that day. Never have I met such a courageous woman. The former queen of Freeport accounted well for herself as well. It pained me deeply to see the young maids that I had trained laying dead on the grounds around us. They fought so valiantly. I knew that our end was near when I saw the former queen fall with an arrow through her heart. At last, it was just a few of us and Lady Alani left. The Teir`Dal had us restrained when that **SMURF** D’Vinn walked up. There were some words exchanged and D’Vinn scratched me with his poisoned dirk. He then stabbed Lady Alani through the heart with it. I knew I was dieing. Lady Alani was dead in my arms. I saw the manor on fire and I rushed in to gather the things I knew would mean the most to Lord Gilliad and his son when they returned, the Shadowbane family swords and the music boxes Lady Alani had made. I pulled Lady Alani’s parents’ bodies from their burning apartment behind the smithy so they too could receive a proper burial. I returned to Lady Alani’s body and wept until Lord Gilliad returned. I saw the pain in his eyes and the horror in young Gilliadson’s. We gathered the bodies and buried them on the land. The manor was too far gone to save so we just let it burn to the ground. Somehow we all felt that D’Lere was behind this for the tracks that the Teir`Dal left lead toward Freeport. I gave Lord Gilliad and his son their music boxes and the Shadowbane swords. Lord Gilliad put me on his horse and we rode to the Temple of Marr in Freeport. Lord Gilliad and Gilliadson stayed with me until I passed on.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Chapter 3 The New Druid&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I went to the druid guild masters in Rivervale to begin my training. I was outfitted with some basic clothing and a very nice little club. I was given some patterns and a list of materials needed as well as a kit to make the pieces of leather armor that were magically empowered to protect me from the dangers of the world. I would go out into the Misty Thicket and hunt the creatures that had the items that I needed to make the armor and then fashion each piece with the tools in the kit. It wasn’t long before I was wearing a full set of Moss Toe armor. I learned my spells also very quickly. One final quest was needed. I had to investigate the some ruins where some rats were becoming diseased and some undead Halflings were hanging around. I discovered that the perpetrator of this was a very rude Halfling traitor in the Southeast corner of Misty Thicket. I was commissioned to kill this traitor and bring back his head. So I felt I was ready for this challenge until I arrived at his cottage and found two large wolves guarding it. I resolved myself to complete this mission or die in the process. I managed to calm one of the wolves and decided I would try to take out the other one first so I hit him with my snare spell. He somehow resisted it and came after me with the traitor behind him. I stood toe to toe with the traitor for a few rounds of fighting and realized that he was going to get the better of me if I stuck around. I ran back toward Rivervale with the traitor and the one wolf in pursuit. As I neared the town a Koada`Dal priestess saw the plight I was in and intervened on my behalf. She was a powerful one indeed. The traitor and his pet both fell dead behind me. I thanked the priestess and collected the traitor’s head to give to my guild master. I was given a scimitar and some more instructions on how to make it magical. I went back to the Thicket and found a giant fruit bat and killed it. I took one of its wings and went to the forge in town. I sharpened the scimitar up with a stone and then gave the smith the sharpened scimitar and the fruit bat wing. He did a little work on it in the forge and returned it to me. I could feel the magic in the blade. I started traveling around Norrath some. Apparently, I had been away for a while, though it seemed like just a few minutes. There were portals now that connected various parts of Norrath to a place called New Tanaan. The ships no longer ran from the various city ports but instead there were wizards at each of the docks to transport people magically from one port to another. There was a portal to New Tanaan not too far from Rivervale so I went to it. It looked like a book on a pedestal. I walked up and laid my hand on it and I was suddenly in a different place looking at a stone that had my home city’s name carved into it. I stepped down from the small platform and walked into the busiest city I had ever seen. I saw all kinds of people here including some feline creatures called Vah Shir and some frog-like creatures called Frogloks. When I first encountered a Teir`Dal here I instinctively cast my snare spell on him and was about to conjure up a stinging swarm when I noticed that my snare spell never even landed. It was as if I had never cast it. He walked up to me with a big smile on his face and greeted me most kindly.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Do not be afraid little one. No one here can harm you nor can you harm him or her. In this place no harmful magic can be used nor any weapons. Please see for your self. Try to strike me with your blade.” Said the Teir`Dal. I drew my scimitar and tried to swing it at him but the blade would not touch him. “I cannot harm you either. This is a neutral place where all abide as peacefully as we can. All speak freely here and the only thing that will hurt you may be some of the words here.” I was amazed to say the least. I took my leave of the Teir`Dal and continued wandering the city. I walked into a massive library where there were millions of books. There were people in there that sold spells for the various practitioners of magic. I found a druid merchant who was selling some spells that I knew I could use soon so I bought them from him. I also found a map in there of the city that I could take with me. Using the map, I located the stone portal to Kelethin. I decided I would go visit the Fier`Dal druids.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Chapter 4 Catching Up&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I arrived in the Greater Faydark forest a little southeast of the southern lift into Kelethin. I had not gone far from the portal when I met a wolf. He seemed friendly enough. A voice whispered in my head.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;“Greetings Willanaome. Tunare sent me to greet you and to let you know that your friends, the Shadowbanes live here. I am aware that you are not to contact them just yet but if you would like to follow me to the ruined druid circle I will tell you all I know about their deeds since they have been here.” I will tell you that since I have returned to Norrath I discovered that I could talk to the friendly animals such as wolves and bears so hearing from this wolf was not a surprise in itself. Hearing that I had stumbled upon the Shadowbanes however was. I followed the wolf to the druid rings and we sat there while I listened to all he had to tell me. He told me of great battles between the Elves here and the Orcs of Crushbone. My heart was glad to hear of Lord Gilliad falling in love with Mariel of Felwithe and marrying her. I wept when he told me that Lord Gilliad had been slain by D’Vinn. Then he told me of Gilliadson defeating D’Vinn in a daring raid on Crushbone. I was overjoyed to hear of Gilliadson finding love in Rihki a Koada`Dal priestess. The wolf then told me of Gilliadson bringing Rihki’s body back after his fight with Lucan D’Lere in Freeport. I learned about his friends Zephistophiles the bard and his chronicler, Elwinde and Sineliniel the twin Koada`Dal arcanists, Shinu a Vah Shir Warrior and Whoos the Froglok priest and his wife Sanlacy the Barbarian Shaman. Finally, the wolf told me of Lady Obsecion of Felwithe, a Tunarean Knight who was once in the service of Firiona Vie herself, who Gilliadson had fallen in love with and married. I also learned that the two of them went off to the Plane of Sky and returned with the flaming swords called Fiery Avengers. It seemed like things were looking up for Gilliadson and his bride. They just had not produced any children yet. The wolf told me that they were both away now seeking to acquire Fiery Defenders. I thanked the wolf for the tales and went on my way to Kelethin. I knew that even if Gilliadson saw me, he would not recognize me but I was not sure I could contain myself if I saw him. I found the druid guild masters and pledged my service to them for a few seasons. So now, I hunt the Orcs of Crushbone and wait to here more news of Gilliadson.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Chapter 5: A Wandering Druid&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;After my time of service to the Fier`Dal druids was over, I went to my gravesite in the Commonlands and retrieved my music box. At first I was not sure if this new body would be able to open the box since they were made to be opened only by their owners. I covered the grave back up and then knelt between the graves of Lady Alani and Lord Gilliad as I wept over them. I promised them that I would do my best to watch over their son when I was restored to him. But for now I must go where Lord Karana sends me.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I went to Luclin to explore the hidden moon some. I signed on with the houses of Fordel and Midst in Shadow Haven to police the Paludal Caverns for a few seasons. I fought the rogues there in the caverns until my time of service was completed. I decided I would visit the plains that were named after my God and perform my druidic duties there. I completed my service to Karana there and wandered to Stonebrunt to aid the Kejekans there with their problems with the Heretic invaders and the Kobolds. While there in Stonebrunt I learned of Zephistophiles' coming joining. I decided to ask the Kejekans if they had a blade suitable as a wedding present for Gilliadson's friend. They told me that one of the villagers had a couple of them that he might be persuaded to give me. When I went to see him, I saw that his wife was ill. I tried to cure her with my own druid magic but it would not work. He sent me to the village Shaman who told me of a cure that she was working on but needed a few more ingredients and asked me if I would gather them for her. I told her I would. She gave me a bag and I went on my way through the area searching for the items needed. I ported to South Ro and hunted some cistern asps for their poison glands. After I salvaged two of them, I returned to Stonebrunt and hunted Kejekan tigers for two skins. I then collected two panda claws. I had to forage around for the last two items, a bamboo shoot and Kejekan palm fruit. Once I had al the items in the bag I returned to the village and gave it to the shaman. She did a little work and handed me a potion to take to the villager's sick wife. The potion cured her and he was so happy that he gave me two swords that he called Wakizashi of the Frozen Skies for Zephistophiles. I decided also to get something for his bride-to-be, who is a monk. I heard that there are large sabretooth tigers in the area called Snowbeast whose hides make wonderful footwear for monks. I knew the tiger was going to be more than I could handle so I sent a message to Sineliniel asking for her assistance.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;When Sineliniel arrived in Stonebrunt she was not sure of who I actually was. I swore her to secrecy before I pulled out my music box and played the melody that was contained in it. I handed her my box and she could see that it was one of the boxes made for Lady Shadowbane as gifts. She also knew that the boxes would only play their melodies for their owners. Lord Gilliad's box was buried in the Commonlands with the part of his remains interred there. Gilliadson still carried his box with him. I told Sineliniel that I would contact Gilliadson when I received permission from Karana to do so. Sineliniel sent for Lady Obsecion to come assist us but did not tell her who I was other than a friend. We hunted for one of those tigers for a long time before we found one. When the fight was over however the skin was ruined too badly to make the sandals. We decided to take a break and go back to it the next day.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;The next day Sanlacy's mother, Jildarie and another friend named Kattcankil came to assist us. It did not take us long to find another Snowbeast. This time we were more careful in killing it and managed to get enough material to make two pairs of the footpads so we gave one pair to Kattcankil.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;I secretly attended the wedding and it was quite lovely. Ruetamerras did a wonderful ceremony. Gilliadson was not able to attend due to being away on a mission so his Daughter, Lutiana, stood in for him. She is quite a lovely child. From what I was able to see, she has her father's eyes and her mother's hair. She will grow into a great Lady Knight one day. Zephistophiles was happy with the two swords I gave him. I got to sit down and talk with him at great length without revealing who I was. He is a great Loremaster. We discussed Norrathian history among other topics. He told me a few of his tales of Gilliadson, which I had already heard from the wolves but I listened to his renditions anyway.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Word from Karana arrived to me in the thunder of a storm. I will be allowed to finally rejoin the Shadowbane family. I sent word to Sineliniel to let her know and asked her to set up a meeting for me with Obsecion and Lutiana. I have been listening to my music box quite a bit lately. It seems to calm my anxiety over this meeting. I wonder how Gilliadson will react when he hears of me.&amp;nbsp; The only proof I can offer them as to my real identity is my music box.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
