    <item>
      <title>A Savior of the Pale Rose is Born</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Roleplaying&amp;message.id=12448#M12448</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The wind coming off of the frozen tundra east of Halas chilled one to the bone. Long past battles fought here left the landscape barren and uninhabitable. Old ruins dotted the landscape no matter which way one looked. Ancient statues, much larger than the wolly mammoths that normally roamed the countryside, could be seen everywhere.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Jandoleer, the young shaman, was on a quest, given to him by a well known merchant of Halas. Jan was trudging through the snow drifts and making only marginal headway, but was determined to continue forward on desolate Everfrost Peaks. In the distance, was a young boy no more than six seasons of age. He, too was making limited progress in the snowdrifts. Jan had been following the child for more than an hour. Not by design, but simply for that was the way each were headed and Jandoleer was not interested in a traveling companion.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Suddenly, an orc appeared in the distance. Apparently he had been killing and plundering the wildlife in the area and had grown bored simply laying waste to the fauna of the frozen tundra. He noticed the child struggling to make way in the snow and moved quickly to interecept him. With a blood curdling yell, the massive orc charged the boy with his rusty sword swinging over his head. Not paying attention to the danger around him, the lad was struck a glancing blow by the oncoming orc. The child stumbled, let out a cry and started running back in the direction he had come. Back toward Jandoleer. The bright red blood from a gash on his forehead, and fear, blinded him to the fact that someone was nearby and in an instant ran right into Jan. Running into the young shaman was like crashing into the side of a barn. The blow was so severe that it completely knocked the boy unconscious.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Jandoleer pulled his weapon and with a cry, began chanting a shamanistic spell. The orc that was bearing down on the young shaman and the boy suddenly froze in his tracks. Calmly, and with practiced ease, Jandoleer dodged a slash from the orc. Backing up out of range, Jan again cast another spell, and the hate faded in the orcs eyes. The life within the orc drained in a flash leaving a corpse where seconds before was a living, breathing, dealer of death.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Once he was sure the orc was no longer a threat, Jandoleer turned to the boy lying in the snow. The child's forehead had a terrible, though not life threatening, gash which was bleeding profusely. Again raising his hands out over the lad, Jandoleer again chanted another spell. The pale light of healing spread out over the child's body. The injury on his head slowly closed, leaving what would obviously be a scar which he would carry the rest of his life. As the boy awoke and realised where he was, rather than thanking the shaman for having saved his life, he jump up from the snow and ran off in the direction of Halas, screaming in terror. Jan smiled once he was sure the boy was headed in the right direction and turned back toward the direction he had been traveling. Back to his own quest.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;End Chapter 1&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Thu, 09 Mar 2006 15:57:16 GMT</pubDate>
      <author>BoarMaster</author>
      <guid>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Roleplaying&amp;message.id=12448#M12448</guid>
