    <item>
      <title>The dragon, the shattered blade, and the gashed armor</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Roleplaying&amp;message.id=12447#M12447</link>
      <description>So there I was, walking the halls of the great Temple of Veeshan, a place that I had worked hard to to be blessed enough to enter without being destroyed by the guardian drakes and dragons. I was walking down the halls, the walls stained with the blood of many who failed in thier attempts to slay these beast of legend. The floors were warm, but scuffed by the boots of my fallen brethren. I could still hear the battles raging, the dragons unleashing thier powerful roars that send many running in fear, and the bright glow of thier magnificent magics filling the long coridors. The tools of destruction were scattered around the halls, obviously dropped by those trying to find an exit. It was then that I noticed the glow of my holy blade reflecting from a blade upon the ground. I kneeled down and took a look at the blade, tried to resist the urge to handle the blade, but my curiousity had bested me.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As I removed my guantlets to feel the weight of the blade for myself, the indentation of the former owners hand in the hilt, and the swiftness of the blade through the air. I started to have a vision, a most horrible vision indeed. I see several people surrounding me, of many backgrounds, from many proffessions. To my left were priest cowering behind a wall, peeking out occasional to chant a few words and send the bright glow of a heal upon a falling comrade. To my right were archers wielding the most magnicent bows, cocking back the string with pristine arrows lined and aimed for what I had saw next. I looked foward to see a massive dragon, it must have stood six stories tall, surrounded by brave men and women wielding the majestic weapons they had found in thier adventures. In front of the dragon was a knight, much alike myself in my younger days, follying his swings and fizzleing the spells between the swipes of this massive dragon's claws.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Then the dragon's claw came down for the first time, knocking him back a large distance, tearing his shield in two rendering it useless. He must have flown back a good twenty feet, stood up and rushed toward the dragon with his sword high in the air, letting out a most powerful yaulp. As he neared the dragon several wizards and magicians rushed toward the dragon, wiggled thier fingers, chanted some words in an arcane tongue and the dragon's skin ignited in the most brilliant display of magics. The dragon roared loudly, and they took off running for cover. &amp;quot;There is no escape for you mortal !&amp;quot;, he bellowed summoning a wizard in front of him. Shortly after came his claw, tearing the limbs from the poor man's body, leaving him in a most un-recoverable pile of human ramains.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As the fight progressed several had died from this dragon's fierce power, but knight still persevered, standing face to face with this monsterous beast, hacking and slashing, casting one spell after another in an attempt to keep the dragon's attention. But then something went wrong, a cleric passed out from exhuastion, another attempting to meditate to regain strength to land just a few more heals. But the dragon's powerful magic filled the halls, awaking the cleric from his meditation and weaking the entire force. Corpses were strewn about all over the place, on a few braves remained to finish the beast, who was starting to wear down. It's legs were bleeding most fatally, stomache almost completely unscaled, and skin that was nearly burned to a crisp.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The dragon now realized he was nearing his death, and these brave warriors were still going strong despite thier dwindling numbers. He turned and attempted to flee, calling out for help, but none of them wanted anything to do with him. He was a shame to his race, nearly defeated by mere mortals, unable to guard the inner sanctum of thier great temple. It was then, the knight rushed under the massive being, thrust his sword upwards and pierce the thick skin of the beast. The dragon stumbled, and turned to face the knight. It's eyes were begging for relief, but it wasn't going down just yet. Again he raised his massive claw, swooped down and gashed through the knights thick armor, exposing the innards of his chest. The priest chanted many heals but none were able to save this now fallen knight. In one last breath he said his prayer, asking his god, Mithaniel Marr, to grant his brethren safe passage out of the temple.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Everything was blurry after that, and fading away back to the temple that I now know. The sword in my hand began to crack, and shattered shortly after. A loud crackle erupted from the blade, acompanied by a bright glow flowing upward. I think it may have been the knight's soul finally leaving this plane of existing and moving into the afterlife, but only he and Lord Mithaniel Marr know for certain what happend during that instant.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;Hey Shill, you ok? Your looking a little pale bro&amp;quot;, my friend asked me from down the hall.&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;Yeah i'm fine, I think i've seen all i can handle of this place&amp;quot;, I replied to him.&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;What's that broken sword in your hand?&amp;quot;, he asked.&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;Just a remnent of a once great knight&amp;quot;, i said to him as i placed the sword back on the ground where I found it.&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;Rest in piece brave knight. I will see to it the bards transcribe your battle into the history books of Myrist&amp;quot;, I uttered while placing my guantlet back onto my hand.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
